    "Network and CommunitiesA comprehensive review of network theory is beyond the scope of this paper and we refer the reader to [58,84] for more details.",
    "We just define sufficient terminology to be able to understand our method.A network is represented by a graph G = (V, E) where V is the set of vertices and E is the set of edges.",
    "A network may be unweighted, in which case there is a binary alternative between the existence or non-existence of an edge e i,j between any two vertices v i, v j ∈ V that indicates a relation- ship between those vertices.",
    "A network may be weighted, in which case an edge e i,j has an associated weight w i,j which is a numeric value that characterizes in some way the relationship between vertices v i and v j.",
    "The degree of a vertex v i, denoted k i, is the number of edges connected to that vertex, i.e., k i = |{e i,j ∶ v j ∈ V}|."
  ],
